-16","volume":"126","issue":"502","pages":"643-647","abstract":"","topics":["political"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw077"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw073","title":"Aesthetics as Philosophy of Perception, by Bence Nanay.","authors":["Ophelia Deroy"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-02-14","volume":"126","issue":"502","pages":"635-643","abstract":"","topics":["aesthetics","mind"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw073"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw026","title":"Counting Incompossibles","authors":["Peter Fritz","Jeremy Goodman"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-02-02","volume":"126","issue":"504","pages":"1063-1108","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw026"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw039","title":"Anti-Intellectualism","authors":["Blake Roeber"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-02-01","volume":"127","issue":"506","pages":"437-466","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw039"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw062","title":"The Logical Structure of Kinds, by Eric Funkhouser.","authors":["Joseph Laporte"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-02-01","volume":"126","issue":"502","pages":"627-631","abstract":"","topics":["logic"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw062"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzv189","title":"Against the Russellian Open Future","authors":["Anders J Schoubye","Brian Rabern"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-23","volume":"126","issue":"504","pages":"1217-1237","abstract":"Todd (2016) proposes an analysis of future-directed sentences, in particular sentences of the form ‘will()’, that is based on the classic Russellian analysis of definite descriptions. Todd’s analysis is supposed to vindicate the claim that the future is metaphysically open while retaining a simple Ockhamist semantics of future contingents and the principles of classical logic, i.e. bivalence and the law of excluded middle. Consequently, an open futurist can straightforwardly retain classical logic without appeal to supervaluations, determinacy operators, or any further controversial semantical or metaphysical complication. In this paper, we will show that this quasi-Russellian analysis of ‘will’ both lacks linguistic motivation and faces a variety of significant problems. In particular, we show that the standard arguments for Russell's treatment of definite descriptions fail to apply to statements of the form ‘will()’.","topics":["language","logic","metaphysics"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzv189"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw035","title":"Closure Scepticism and The Vat Argument","authors":["Joshua Rowan Thorpe"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-23","volume":null,"issue":null,"pages":"fzw035","abstract":"","topics":["epistemology"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw035"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzv194","title":"What Verities May Be","authors":["Igor Douven","Lieven Decock"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-22","volume":null,"issue":null,"pages":"fzv194","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzv194"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzv182","title":"Deflationism, Arithmetic, and the Argument from Conservativeness","authors":["Daniel Waxman"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-22","volume":null,"issue":null,"pages":"fzv182","abstract":"","topics":["logic"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzv182"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzw023","title":"What You’re Rationally Required to Do and What You Ought to Do (Are the Same Thing!)","authors":["Errol Lord"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-22","volume":null,"issue":null,"pages":"fzw023","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/mind/fzw023"},{"doi":"10.1093/mind/fzv192","title":"Maximally Consistent Sets of Instances of Naive Comprehension","authors":["Luca Incurvati","Julien Murzi"],"journal":"mind","published":"2017-01-22","volume":null,"issue":null,"pages":"fzv192","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"ur